Dear Hinckley Families:
We are excited to meet students virtually from 6-7:30 p.m. on Thursday, September 10 for our annual Open House. As a reminder, Open House will occur virtually this year through Zoom. Classroom teachers will be sending Zoom links directly to families. If you do not receive this Zoom link by Wednesday, September 9, please contact your child's teacher. A schedule (below) has been created to encourage families to log in at scheduled times in order to meet as many classmates as possible. In addition, a general school overview has been created for your review.

Link: Hinckley Elementary Overview
Kindergarten: 6 PM
1st Grade: 6:15 PM
2nd Grade: 6:30 PM
3rd Grade: 6:45 PM
4th Grade: 7 PM
5th Grade: 7:15 PM

If you are unable to make the specific time as stated above, the Zoom links will be open for the full Open House duration (6-7:30 p.m.).

We look forward to a great school year! Thank you!

post_text:
The Highland Hornets will face off against North Royalton at their home opener at 7 p.m. on September 4 at the Highland Stadium.

Due to the recent state order llimiting the number of spectator capacity at athletic events, a maximum of 4 family members of Highland football players, cheerleaders and the Marching Band, will be permitted to attend the games. Tickets will not be sold at the gate.

FREE Live Streaming! ~ In an effort to have Hornet fans tune in to the action, we are offering all home football games via live stream! To stream the game live, visit: https://hls.media/

Additional Considerations:

Tailgating is prohibited this year to adhere to orders of the Ohio Department of Health.
All spectators must be seated in the bleachers or in designated areas.
Face masks are required and physical distancing guidelines will be enforced.
Spectators (without tickets) are not permiited to congregate outside of the stadium, as this would be counted toward our venue capacity limit.

Any questions, please call the Highland Athletic Office at 330-239-1901, ext. 5400.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,

We are excited to welcome students back for the 2020-2021 academic year!

We all know this school year is going to look very different from anything we have ever experienced and we will no doubt face numerous challenges along the way; but as we begin to work our way back in a responsible manner, I am confident that we will come together as a school community and persevere through this unprecedented time.

In addition to the district’s 2020-21 Reopening Plan we provided in August, we now present students and families with the new “Teaching & Learning Guidelines” (including building schedules) for Option 1 (Traditional In-Person Learning, with Hybrid and Home Distance Learning Contingency Plans). Download HERE.

Highland Middle School Supply & Schedule Pick Up:

Wednesday, September 2

Last names A-K from 4-6 p.m.
Last names L-Z from 6-8 p.m.

Thursday, September 3

Last names L-Z from 4-6 p.m.
Last names A-K from 6-8 p.m.



Students (and/or parents) should enter the main entrance (front doors) of the building and proceed to the West Gym. Face masks are required to enter the building.

All materials are organized alphabetically by grade. Each HMS student (including those registered for Highland's Virtual Learning Academy) will receive the following:

Welcome letter
Class schedule
Student handbook
Mask lanyard
PTO information
One-to-One Chromebook Agreement (to be signed by parent)
Supply kit (if purchased)
FinalForms reminder (if applicable)
2019-2020 yearbook (if purchased). Yearbooks for last year's 8th graders are also available for pick up.

After picking up materials in the West Gym, students are encouraged to find their first-period class. Thank you!

post_text:
Dear Highland Parents and Guardians,

In preparation for the upcoming school year, the district will need to collect all Chromebooks that were loaned to families last spring. We have established a collection process for the smooth return of these devices. We ask that you please return the equipment to Highland High School between the hours of 7:30 a.m. and 4 p.m., beginning Monday, August 31 through Thursday, September 3.

When you arrive at the high school, enter through the lower level entrance doors of the building (lower level parking lot). Facemasks are required. There will be tables available for you to drop off Chromebook(s) and charger(s). It would be helpful to include your child’s name and student ID on the Chromebook(s), but not necessary, as each device was registered during the checkout process.

The Technology Department will need to disinfect and return the Chromebooks to the classrooms where initially taken from in order to have an adequate supply for students when they return to school on September 14-15.

post_text:
Below is the Highland Local Schools Hybrid Calendar for the 2020-21 academic year. As stated in our reopening plan, we will begin the school year on the hybrid learning model in an effort to facilitate the proper transition back to school and allow for additional health and safety training of our students and staff.

From September 14-25, students will return to in-person learning using a phased-in, staggered schedule (Hybrid Model – 50% of students each day, alternating days).

Students will be assigned into one of two groups – Green or White cohort.

Green: Monday, Wednesday, every other Friday (Last names A-K)

Start Day is Monday, September 14

White: Tuesday, Thursday, every other Friday (Last names L-Z)

Start Day is Tuesday, September 15

This grouping would be the same one used for the Hybrid Model, if necessary
Students will be assigned school work on those days not in school buildings

Please download the Hybrid Calendar HERE.

Then, on September 28, all Highland students report to school.

post_text:
Beginning September 4, parents can log in to their child's PowerSchool account to obtain the most current bus information for the 2020-21 school year. Information listed in PowerSchool prior to September 4 may have been modified and parents should verify the information prior to the first day of school for their child.

Please note, this will only work by logging in as your child. Do not create a new PowerSchool parent account.

Go to www.highlandschools.org > click on Student Portal (under Quick Links, left side of page) > click on PowerSchool Sign In
Login: first initial, last name, last two digits of the student ID number
Password: first initial, last initial, full student ID number
Example: If your student’s name is Rob Henry with a student ID of 555518, the login would be rhenry18. The password would be rh555518 (first initial, last initial, student ID number)

Dear Highland Parents/Guardians,

The Highland Board of Education held a special meeting on 8/3 to discuss the updated reopening plan for the 2020-21 school year. As with the initial draft plan, the first priority remains the health and safety of our students and staff.

The recommendations within the plan are based upon the best scientific and medical information available to us at this time. We ask that you carefully review the plan, which includes the district's facemask requirement and updated start dates for the school year. The board also adopted a newly revised 2020-2021 academic calendar. It is attached for your convenience and also available on our website at www.highlandschools.org.

As stated previously, we realize there is no one perfect solution that will meet the needs of every single person affiliated with the Highland Local School District. However, we remain hopeful that we can continue to work collectively on behalf of our school community.

2020-21 REOPENING PLAN
2020-21 Academic Year Calendar

Thank you,
Catherine Aukerman, Superintendent

post_text:
Congratulations to Highland High School Speech & Debate Team Coach Mrs. Suzette Burtoft who was recognized as a "Double Diamond" Coach during the National Speech and Debate Tournament held in June.

Diamond Coach awards reflect excellence and longevity in the activity. A coach’s first Diamond is earned when they receive 15,000 points and have been coaching in the Association for at least five years since achieving the degree of merit (25 points). Five years must pass between each new diamond award, and 15,000 points must be earned to receive a second diamond. An additional 30,000 points must be earned and five years must pass for each additional diamond. Coaches who have received diamond awards during the current academic year are recognized during the Donus D. Roberts Diamond Assembly at that year’s National Tournament.

Mrs. Burtoft was also named "Coach of the Year for Ohio" and is now eligible for the National Coach of the Year Award to be presented next year.

Highland freshman Hannah Tramonte needs your vote FOR THE WIN! Hannah has made it to the final three contestants in Broadway World’s Next On Stage’s Competition out of 700 high school students nationwide! The winner is decided by the most number of public votes, so please take a few seconds to help Highland’s own take the crown. You can vote once per email and must confirm your vote through your email address for it to count. Cast your vote through the link below by Thursday, July 2 at midnight. Tune in at 8 p.m. on Monday July 6 through Broadway World’s Facebook page when they announce the winner live! Thank you so for supporting Hannah!

https://www.broadwayworld.com/nextonstagehighschool/hannah-tramonte

Hannah is the daughter of Joe and Stacy Tramonte, both alumni of Highland High School, and residents of Sharon Township. Hannah's dream is to one day perform on Broadway.

Sharon Elementary teacher Mrs. Julie Boggs had a WIG (Wildly Important Goal) with her class this school year to run a marathon. But with everything going on, all local marathons are now being cancelled. So today as part of 5k mayhem, Mrs. Boggs ran 30 miles around her home -- 1 mile for each of her students! Next Level Prep ACT & SAT Preparation Seminars
Weekly seminars all summer long, starting June 1.
Special price is just $59 for Highland HS students.

Registering is as simple as 1, 2, 3:

1. Click on the link https://nlpohio.com/register-for-a-student-seminar/ and select the seminar that fits your student’s schedule.
2. At checkout, enter the coupon code hghlnd2020 (lower-case letters, case sensitive) to get the Highland student special price of $59.
3. Enter the requested information (address & email are particularly important so we can send resource materials & login information prior to your seminar), using a credit card for the $59 payment.

Please remember the deadline for registering is Thursday noon prior to the start of each Monday seminar.

Visit our website, https://nlpohio.com, to learn more about Next Level Prep & our ACT & SAT seminars.

Next Level Prep, 1805 O’Brien Rd., Columbus, OH, 43228
Call Dave Dobos at 614-580-7380 or email dave@nlpohio.com with any questions.

DEADLINE APPROACHING TO ORDER A STAR AWARD!

Show your appreciation during this unprecedented time! Order a Highland Foundation STAR Award for that special teacher, administrator, bus driver or staff member!

Deadline for submission is May 22. Awards will be delivered between May 27-29. Order your STAR and pay online at http://www.highlandfoundation.org/Content2/44.

The Staff and Teacher Award Recognition (STAR) program proudly honors a Highland teacher, staff or community member for their outstanding work and achievements. Each award recipient is presented with a certificate and either a box of bonbons or a Highland etched diamond ornament. A personal note from the donor can also be included. Proceeds from the STAR Award program are used to fund unique and innovative learning opportunities for Highland Local Schools and the community.

On Tuesday, May 19, Wednesday, May 20 and Thursday, May 21, students (with one parent/guardian) may return to school to clean out their desks, lockers and pick up any personal belongings that remain at school. *(Please note that Senior students have a separate schedule that will be communicated from HHS).

To provide as much flexibility as we can for families, while limiting the overall number of people in our buildings at one time, the following schedule has been developed. Each portion of the alphabet has been scheduled at different times over the course of three days. In order to adhere to proper physical distancing protocols, we ask that you come on only one of the dates and times that corresponds to your child’s last name.

Highland Fort Challenge is ON!
Today's Spirit Day theme is...."Who can build the best home fort?"

Calling on all home fort builders! You know how this goes. First, get your parents’ permission.

Who will build the best home fort? The challenge is on!

BICENTENNIAL CELEBRATION POSTPONED ~
Granger Bicentennial Committee has decided to postpone the Bicentennial Celebration planned for June 2020 due to concerns over COVID-19.

The celebration has been rescheduled for June 25, 26 and 27, 2021. The committee will continue to work hard to make it a grand celebration for Granger’s Bicentennial + One! Feel free to visit their website at www.grangerhs.com. Details and an updated timeline will be posted when it becomes available.

According to the 2020 U.S. News & World Report Best High Schools Rankings released on April 21, Highland High School is ranked 13th out of 129 high schools in the Cleveland Metro area, 36th among Ohio’s 902 high schools and 1,013th out of 17,792 high schools nationally.

U.S. News evaluated over 24,000 public high schools nationwide, with more than 17,000 schools ranked. The highest ranked public schools are those whose attendees demonstrated outstanding outcomes above expectations in math and reading state assessments, passed a diverse array of college-level exams and graduated in high proportions.

A Message from Feeding Medina County ~

Feeding Medina County has been holding a county wide food distribution for the past three weeks with others scheduled on April 9 and April 16.

It is held at the Medina County Fairgrounds and starts at 7:30 a.m. People need to have a photo ID and an empty trunk and are advised to arrive before 7:30 a.m. You will be directed to stay in your car and move through the line. Thank you!

post_text:
Last week, the Governor of Virginia issued a Stay-At-Home order until June 10. Maryland’s Governor also issued a Stay-At-Home order without an end date. Given this information and considering the health and well being of our students and our community, we have made the difficult decision to cancel the 8th grade trip to Washington, D.C.

As a part of the trip, all participants have travel insurance. Nowak Tours has already begun the cancellation process with the insurance company and we are providing the information needed to process the request. Families will receive a check directly from the insurance company. We do not have a timeline on when those checks will be mailed, but we will update families when the information is available.

Again, we understand how excited our students were to have this opportunity and we are saddened by the global circumstances surrounding this decision. Thank you for your continued patience and support.

Thank you Highland Teachers, Staff and Administrators for Your Generosity!

On April 2, Superintendent Catherine Aukerman traveled to each Highland school building to gather disinfecting wipes, hand sanitizers, gloves and masks, all donated from our awesome staff, which were ultimately delivered to Akron Children's Hospital, UH Hospitals and Western Reserve Hospital. She then separated and boxed the supplies for each location.

A Highland mom initially reached our to one of our principals to see if any supplies could be donated and the staff responded in typical Highland style! The donations will certainly make a huge impact on these healthcare facilities and their patients. THANK YOU!!

Join the Cast of “Our Town: Granger” and Help Celebrate the Township's Bicentennial!

Assuming the Granger Township Bicentennial Celebration can move forward, the committee is getting ready to fill the stage. For the production on Friday, June 26, 33 cast members are needed: kids, young adults and adults. Director Bryan Mravec (pictured) is ready to put YOU on the Highland High School stage!

Due to social distancing, the committee is unable to hold in-person auditions (as stated on the form) so they will be using alternate means. If interested, please sign up via the audition form. Then they can assign parts based on questionsthat will be sent to you. They hope to have all parts assigned by the end of April so cast members can begin to learn their lines!

Please pass this on to anyone who might be interested!

Sign up here: https://forms.gle/2phqAzRgd3uPvzyi6

On March 20, The College Board announced changes to the Advanced Placement tests for 2020 in response to the Coronavirus. Traditional face-to-face exam administrations will not take place. Students will be able to test from home and be able to choose from two separate dates. Content for most testing has been adjusted to reflect what students would have covered through early March. Information about the reduced scope of content that will be covered on each 2020 AP Exam is currently posted on AP Central®.

Additional preparation resources will be available beginning on March 25. Requirements for portfolio submissions have also changed. Full information, including specific test dates and the free-response question types for every AP exam will be posted by April 3.

HMS Pi Day Winners ~
Highland Middle School students in Mrs. Anna Taylor's math classes celebrated Pi Day on March 13 with the annual Pi Digits Memorization Contest. Pi Day is an annual celebration of the mathematical constant π (pi). Congratulations to 8th grade winners Kate Critchett (1st place), 141 digits memorized; Sydney Campbell (2nd place), 103 digits; and Faye Lee (3rd place), 68 digits. Winners each received a pie, of course!

Pictured from left are Sydney Campbell, Faye Lee and Kate Critchett.

This evening’s Washington, D.C. Trip Parent Meeting at Highland Middle School is cancelled and will be rescheduled if we travel in May.

We continue to ask for your patience as we work to make decisions on literally hundreds of events, programs and activities occurring within our school district. We base those decisions on the latest guidance from the CDC, the Ohio Department of Health and our local health departments. As always, the health and safety of our students and staff remain our top priority.

Thank you.

Hadler is February Student of Month ~
Highland senior Emily Hadler has been selected as the Medina County Kiwanis February Student of the Month.

Emily is an outstanding student who is involved in numerous AP and Honors classes. She is Yearbook Editor and a member of Student Council, National Honor Society, Medina County Junior Leadership, Students for Impact and is a Peer Leader.

Emily is a four-year member of the Highland tennis year and a three-time State qualifier.She was named Medina County Player of the Year, Suburban League Player of the Year and was presented with the Freshman Pride Award for Athletics.

When not in school or on the tennis court, she enjoys volunteering in the community. Emily volunteers at Medina Hospital, Playhouse Square, Easter Seals and the Human Library. She is also an NHS tutor. In total, she has volunteered over 100 hours of service.

She is the daughter of Gary and Elizabeth Hadler of Granger Township and plans to attend the University of Findlay, where she will study physical therapy.

They learned how harmful nicotine is and the new law of 21 yrs. old to use tobacco or vape products. It was a jam-packed day of information held at the Akron University-Medina Campus. Each student group then put together a list of what they were taking back to their school on the dangers of tobacco and vaping. They will meet with HMS Principal Rob Henry for approval to to work with Deputy Sharon Centner on this leadership project! Knowledge is power! They want their peers to know the harmful effects of vaping!

post_text: The 2020 Highland Safety Week will be offered during two, one week sessions again this summer at Granger Elementary School. The first session will be held June 8-12 and the second from June 15-19. Both sessions will run from 9 a.m. to 12 p.m. The program is designed to introduce and reinforce safety concepts to incoming kindergarten children who are broadening their world by beginning elementary school. It emphasize fun and learning through the use of songs, crafts, role playing, games and field trips. A maximum of 105 students may enroll in the program each week. Cost is $30. Each student will receive a Highland Safety Week t-shirt. A snack will also be provided each day. Registration deadline is April 24. To learn more or to register your child, please download the following form: Highland Safety Week 2020.

Principal Piazza!
Hinckley Elementary 3rd grader Gabby Piazza recently spent the day as the principal of the school, under the guidance of Principal Jim Carpenter. She had a great day taking care of her "new" responsibilities including visiting classrooms, announcements and making sure everything in the building was running smoothly. “Principal for A Day” was one of the many items auctioned off during the 15th Annual Highland Foundation Dinner held on November 2, 2019. Each elementary school participates in the auction and allows the students an up close look at what it's like to serve as a principal. When Gabby is not running an elementary school, she likes to dance, spend time with friends and get ice-cream! She is the daughter of Mike and Heather Piazza of Hinckley Township. Pictured with Gabby is Mr. Carpenter.

post_text:
'Radium Girls' This Weekend!
In the early 1900s, Marie Curie discovered radium, a substance that soon became known for its ability to shrink cancerous tumors. It also glowed in the dark and was seen as miraculous. But for the women who used radium paint to make glow-in-the-dark watches, radium became their death sentence. World famous in the 1920s, the Radium Girls, as they came to be known, sued the company they worked for, fighting for women's rights, worker's rights and the acknowledgement that their lives - and deaths - were worth something.

The Highland High School Thespians will perform on the main stage of the Highland High School Auditorium.

Show times:
3 p.m. and 7 p.m. on Friday, February 28
2 p.m. and 7 p.m. on Saturday, February 29

Tickets are $8 for adults and $6 for students and senior citizens. All tickets are sold at the door. Hope you can join us for the performance!

Set for 6-10 p.m. on Tuesday, March 10 at Highland High School, this class is designed for anyone interested in learning the steps to assist in saving a life. Learn what to do in an emergency if someone stops breathing or their heart stops beating, or assist a person if they are choking or you need to use an AED (Automated External Defibrillator) due to cardiac arrest. Upon completion, students have the option to purchase a 2-year certification card from the Red Cross for $27, payable to the instructor. Registration is $45.

HHS SADD Members Declare PENNY WAR!

Highland High School's SADD members declare a "Penny War" from February 24-28 to benefit the "TextLess Live More" initiative. This organization is dedicated to ending distracted driving and distracted living.

Each day, students will be "dared" to complete a challenge to reduce technology time and spend more time connecting with others. Dares will include reducing screen time, a day free of his/her favorite social media app, having a technology free meal, and using airplane mode while studying, etc.

Please encourage your son or daughter to bring in coins to compete against other classes!

Further information can be found here: https://textlesslivemore.org/

post_text:
Granger Students Get Hands On History Lesson ~

In connection to their study of early Indian civilizations that existed in the Western Hemisphere, Granger Elementary School 5th graders participated in interactive workshops on February 21 with educators from the Cleveland Museum of Natural History. The program's objectives included naming different cultures of prehistoric Ohio Indians and their relative sequence in time, identifying artifacts and their uses, explaining why cultural groups changed their lifestyles, and distinguishing between cultural groups through a comparison of artifacts. It was an afternoon of learning and wonder!

Photos by Tara Ringgenberg

Sharon Elementary 3rd grade students Elijah Madrigal, Amelia Price, Jordan Gryskiewicz have been recognized as Cavs Straight "A" All Stars for the second grading period. Students are randomly selected to receive two free Cavs tickets and a t-shirt as part of the Cleveland Cavaliers and Westfield's Straight “A” All-Stars program. Their name were submitted by their teachers (Mrs. Laura Franz and Mrs. Bernadette Yu) for earning straight A's during second grading period.

This program is open to all students, grades K-8, in Ashtabula, Cuyahoga, Erie, Geauga, Lake, Lorain, Medina, Portage and Summit Counties. All students who earn straight A’s during the first or second grading periods receive a personalized Straight “A” All-Stars certificate and special prize!

Pictured from left are: Elijah, Amelia and Jordan

post_text:
3 Qualify for National S&D Tourney this Summer ~

Congratulations to three Highland Speech and Debate Team members who have officially qualified to compete at the National Speech and Debate Tournament to be held June 14-19 in Albuquerque, New Mexico.

Evan Buck, a two-year national qualifier, will be representing Highland in the category of United States Extemporaneous Speaking, while Madelyn MacMurray and Olivia Russo will team up to compete in the category of Public Forum Debate.

During the National Qualifying Tournament held on February 15, several Highland team members also made it to the semi-final round including Kennedy Shelton, Eris Foutz, Maxwell Mendel, Jacob McPherson and Victoria Farrell. The team has three more opportunities to secure additional National Qualifiers.

Pictured from left are Evan Buck, Madelyn MacMurry and Olivia Russo.

post_text:
Gymnasts Qualify for Districts!
Highland gymnasts had a strong performance on February 16 at the Sectional Meet held at West Geauga High School.

Three gymnasts finished in the top 12 at Sectionals and have qualified for Districts competition next week. Congrats to:

Jenna Pennington, who placed 12th; Mackenzie Yu, 4th on bars, 6th on beam and 9th All Around; and Paige Yu, 2nd on vault, 2nd on bars, 10th on beam, 3rd on floor and 2nd All Around.

Highland placed 5th as a team (136.375) out of the 21 schools. The top 4 teams advanced to district for the team competition. Magnificat outscored Highland by only .375 to place 4th.

The District meet is set for next Saturday at West Geauga High School in Chesterland.

District qualifiers from left are Paige Yu, Mackenzie Yu and Jenna Pennington. Good luck ladies!
